## Conjecture (CPRR)
- Hypothesis 1: llama3.2 supports native tool calling per Meta's
  release notes for the 1B/3B variants. The hard-coded
  ('tools? . #f) was either a copy-paste from an older llama2 era
  config or a misreading of which tier the flag applied to.
- Hypothesis 2: qwen2.5-coder:7b is the right standard-tier
  fallback now that mistral is removed: tool-capable, code-aware,
  available, and the next size up from llama3.2 in our matrix.

## Validation
- Hypothesis 1: direct curl to localhost:11434/api/chat with a
  get_weather tool definition returned a clean tool_calls payload
  with name=get_weather, arguments={city:Tokyo}. Captured in the
  notes for commit 0a7f24c.
- Hypothesis 2: ollama list still shows qwen2.5-coder:7b at 4.7 GB.
  Benchmarked at 22.9 t/s eval, 3.6s total for a square-function
  prompt. Slower than llama3.2 (41.9 t/s) but reliable.

## Refutation / known limits
- llama3.2 STILL sometimes text-formats tool calls instead of using
  the native field — we proved this in tmux. The 'tools? flag
  declares a CAPABILITY, not a guarantee. Sage needs the model
  to actually exercise the capability on each turn.
- qwen2.5-coder:7b also occasionally text-formats. Both small models
  on this hardware are stochastic. The user noted the analogy:
  \"like training a toddler.\" Documented in RELEASE-0.6.0.org as
  the >= 3B model selection rationale.
- The MODEL_TIER_CEILING_FAST default (2000) is unchanged but may
  be wrong now that llama3.2 actually does tool calls. If a tool
  call requires extra context, the auto-switch to standard might
  fire prematurely. Untested in this commit.

## Meta - research / context / deep-dives
- Eval idea: run the same tool-call prompt 20 times against
  llama3.2 and count how often it produces native tool_calls vs
  inline JSON text. Establishes the baseline reliability number
  the user is likely to ask about.
- Compare across families: llama3.2:1b, llama3.2:3b (which is
  ~latest), qwen2.5:0.5b, qwen2.5-coder:0.5b. The user specifically
  asked about a possible \"qwen3.5:0.6\" with tool support — that
  doesn't exist as a tag, but qwen2.5:0.5b is the closest small
  tool-capable option. Worth pulling and benchmarking.
- The fallback parser (ollama-parse-tool-call) only catches
  ```tool fenced blocks. A future enhancement could detect raw
  JSON-shaped tool calls in streamed text. Brittle but might
  recover the unreliable cases.
- Related: docs/MCP-CONTRACT.org (in progress) will document MCP's
  tool-calling contract — likely a more rigorous protocol than
  Ollama's, since MCP servers must declare tools/list up front.
